item.title: G.E. Dishwasher Wheels and Clip/Axle
item.description:
These wheels are for GE dishwashers, see pictures for examples.
There are both skinny and wide wheel .stl files.

The tolerances are tight so that there is little slop in the wheels. You may need to calibrate your extruder steps.

Be sure to use 5% support under the clip and under the curve of the wheel.

You will need to cleanup the wheels and axles to get them to rotate freely.
Putting the wheels on and spinning them and/or adding a drop of oil will help.

item.title: Ender 3 V2 Squash Ball Feet (Rear)
item.description:
The front feet mount without issue on my Ender 3 V2, but the rear feet of 'Dr Boo's CR-10 Squash Feet' do not fit on an Ender 3 V2 due to the PSU mounting on the lower frame rails. This design allows for direct mounting of the feet using three T-nuts plus one of the Phillips head screws used to secure the PSU and does not interfere with the plate.

Only one file is included (left if viewed from the front of the printer), but you obviously need two feet. Mirror the model to print it for the right side.
item.author: ToDumToKnow

item.title: Guitar foot stool
item.description:
A foot stool for playing the guitar.

The platform is 270x150mm and will fit on a CR-10. I printed at 0.30mm layer height with 5 shells and 5 top and bottom layers. I had to drill our the holes a bit and so I increased the clearance by 0.25 mm on the version uploaded here but I didn't print another copy to check clearances. The holes may still need a small amount of drilling. I reversed the inner and outer rail when I built mine - it seems fine so I didn't disassemble it.. You will print 1 platform, 2 bushing, and 2 of each rail. If you go the threaded rod rout for the roller pin (see below), you will need a bushing2 as well. Total print time was around 26 hours printed in 2 jobs - one with platform only, one with everything else.

From a hardware standpoint, I used 5mm x 25mm pan head screws screws to hold the rails together. I used a #10-24 threaded rod cut to length to hold the rails to the platform - I couldn't find long enough metric rod at my hardware store. For the roller pin, I used 3/8" (9.5mm).solid aluminum rod in which I drilled and tapped 5mm x 20mm holes in each end. I set the roller pin up originally to use threaded rod with bushing2 over the rod so I would expect this to work too. I did not test this though. I used washers in some places when I hadn't planned to because I felt it would spread the compression load a bit. I cut the threaded rod too short to use washers though, I guess I'll see if it matters in the long run. I used nylon inset nuts for all 4 nuts.

item.title: Ender 3 V2 Belt 45 PSU & Screen Mounts
item.description:
Mounts to move the Ender 3 V2 PSU to the rear of the Belt 45 conversion frame and mount Ender 3 V2 screen to left side of Belt 45 frame.

V2_PSU_Mount - Requires 2 - Need 4 5X8mm screws and 4 5mm T-Nuts, reuse original 4mm screws. Will also require new 450mm 16awg power cables from PSU to Motherboard (must use appropriate ferrules and connectors)

V2_SCREEN_MOUNT - Designed to mount Ender 3 V2 screen on left side of printer - Need 2 5X8mm screws and 2 5mm T-Nuts

Printed in PLA, .20 layer height, 4 perimeters, 20% infill, no supports

item.title: Ender 3 Direct Drive BTT Smart Filament Sensor Mount
item.description:
For Creality Ender 3/Pro/V2 Printers Converted to Direct Drive Only

Converted my Ender 3 V2 to direct drive and needed a place to mount my BigTreeTech (BTT) Smart Filament Sensor. The mounts I found were located in a place that would restrict the direct drive movement, were not secure, or were mounted on the X-gantry (wanted side mount as my filament dryer sides beside my printer). This mount replaces the back panel of the filament sensor and mounts securely in the stock extruder location.

Hardware needed:

-(4) M3x8mm screws (I used socket head, but I recommend button head for clearance)
-(4) M3 nuts
item.author: ToDumToKnow

item.title: Nocks and Fletching for Wooden Arrows
item.description:
I've been a big fan of Backyard Bowyer and ZNA Productions and their amazing PVC bows. I recently built 2 of their designs using PVC and fiberglass driveway markers and they shoot great, but arrows aren't cheap and every time I shot the 70lb bow they shattered on impact.

$0.74 5/16" oak dowels are quite cheap, though.

So I knocked up some nocks that I printed in ABS and some one-piece fletchings to be printed in TPU and wrapped around the arrow shaft. For arrowheads I'm just using some steel tubing I smashed flat in my vise and shaped/sharpened and glued in place.

item.title: Elegoo Saturn Tools
item.description:
These are my files for my Elegoo Saturn. These were made as a sort of erector set, letting you swap tasks. So drain bottle to bottle, or filter to bottle or filter to fep tray, or even fep tray to fep tray.
The system allows for you to set up additional configurations.
The entire system is on Tinkercad, so if you want to modify, have at it.... https://www.tinkercad.com/things/25UxQbVOvFC-elegoo-tools
I have also included other tools, because I wanted one complete matching set.

Finally, as an added bonus, I started creating Trays for all the tools that come with the tool kit for the Elegoo, and each set of trays fits into the Elegoo Resin Boxes. (I turn mine inside out.)
Sorry if you don't buy your resin from Elegoo, these are made to fit the Elegoo boxes.

I wanted to post before the contest ended, so I am not quite done with the spacers for the trays, but any spacers will work.

I printed in FDM on my elegoo at 1mm nozzle and .35 layer height and really fast speed, so the prints are not pretty, but when I need perfection, I move to the saturn, LOL.

item.title: M4 Bolts and Nuts
item.description:
I did not have long enough bolts for this fan shroud to secure the 5015 fans, and although the fans do indeed fit snug, I didn't like the look of the empty holes. There are two different sizes, both M4 bolts/nuts. The longer ones go in the front. Hex head uses the largest allen wrench that came with the printer (Neptune 2/2S)

No supports or bed adhesion required. Printed at .1 layer height for better threads. Need two of each size. Can be multiplied and printed together if desired.
